Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Trim the @aubergine{1} then halve lengthways. Chop each half 
into four long strips then chop widthways in half. Pop the aubergine onto a large #baking 
tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with @olive oil{} and season with @salt{}, @pepper{} 
and half of the @Sri Lankan curry powder{1}. Toss to coat and roast the aubergine 
until golden brown and soft, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking. Once 
cooked, remove from your oven and set aside.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and sliced). Chop the @paneer{250%g} 
into 2cm chunks. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(grated with a garlic press). 
Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed), then quarter lengthways (no need to peel). Chop widthways 
into small pieces. Roughly chop the @coriander{}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Zest 
the @lime{1/2} and chop into wedges. Chop up the @salted peanuts{25%g} as finely as 
you can.

> If you've added paneer to your meal, chop it into 2cm chunks once you've prepped the onion.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a #medium saucepan{} on a medium high heat. When hot, 
add the paneer to the pan and fry until golden, stirring occasionally, ~{3-4%minutes}. 
Remove to a #plate{}. Pop the pan back on the heat with a drizzle of oil. When hot, 
add the onion and carrot and cook, stirring frequently, until tender, ~{7-8%minutes}. 
Add the remaining Sri Lankan spice, @tomato puree{30%g}, garlic and @red split lentils{50%g} 
and cook for ~{1%minute} stirring frequently. Add the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @water{100%ml} 
(for the curry), @vegetable stock powder{1} and paneer. Stir to combine and simmer 
until the lentils are cooked, ~{20-25%minutes}.

> Step 3 MOD: If you've decided to add paneer to your meal, before you cook the veg, 
heat a drizzle of oil in the saucepan on a medium high heat. When hot, add the paneer 
to the pan and fry until golden, stirring occasionally, 3-4 mins. Remove to a plate. 
Continue with the rest of the step (using the same pan) and add the paneer back into 
the sauce when you add the water and stock.

While the curry cooks, pour the water into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When 
boiling, add @salt{1/4%tsp}, @star anise{1}, stir in the @basmati rice{150%g}, lower 
the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, 
then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another 
~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Once the lentils are soft, add the @baby spinach{100%g} to the curry a handful at a time 
and cook until wilted and piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}. If the curry is a bit thick add 
a touch of @water{}. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Remove the star anise from the rice and fluff with a #fork{}. Share the rice between 
your #bowls{} and top with the curry. Top with the roasted aubergine pieces. In a 
#small bowl{}, combine the chopped peanuts, lime zest, coriander and @olive oil{}. 
Sprinkle over the whole dish and serve with a lime wedge along side for squeezing 
over. Enjoy!